&lt;h2 id=&#34;Considerations&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Considerations&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Considerations&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Considerations&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;I only just started using this.Â  It works for my current implementation.Â  But you may need to tweak it so that it works for you. For example, my assumption here is that you are only dealing with simple types or the page model type you are a proxy for.Â  There is no code here that will handle a situation where the call to a method would return a entirely new page model. Since the code I am testing is a collection of Single Page Applications and I am not testing navigation at this point, this is not a consideration for me.Â  But it would be relatively easy code to implement.Â  If I did that, I would probably handle it but subclassing this main class that does the bulk of the work and override the Try*Member method that needed to deal with that situation.Â  The other possible way of dealing with the situation is to pass in a list of types that need to be wrapped in their own parallelization object as parameters in the constructor and add some generic code in the ParallelPageModel class. Finally, I am well aware that this code may have bugs.Â  If you find one, go ahead and fix it. You can leave a comment so that others will benefit. Â  There is aÂ &lt;a href=&#34;//github.com/DaveMBush/ParallelSeleniumUsingNUnit&#34;&gt;demo project on GitHub.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
